{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 09:19:28.421625", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network reachability and routing analysis\n\nSummary (top-level)\n- Overall the enterprise network and service plane are healthy: hosts obtain DHCP, resolve DNS, and can reach the published web service addresses (10.200.0.0/24) and the load-balancer. ICMP tests to dns_server, web_server_0 and the load_balancer from representative hosts succeed with low latency and no loss.\n- One notable and expected (by design) anomaly: the backend web network 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2) is not reachable from regular host subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24). Packets from hosts toward 20.200.0.0/24 are rejected at the first-hop gateway with “Destination Net Unreachable”.\n- Localization and root cause: the backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is not present/advertised in the OSPF routing domain (no route in the distribution/core routers), so host traffic cannot be routed to that subnet. The backend segment is reachable from the server/load-balancer side but is not injected into the campus routing table.\n\nCurrent health — what is working\n- DHCP reachability: dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) → hosts: ping tests succeed (0% loss).\n- DNS and service reachability: dns_server (10.200.0.2) and web_server_0..3 (10.200.0.3..6) are reachable from hosts (pings successful).\n- Load balancer (10.200.0.7) reaches backend servers (20.200.0.2 etc) and can reach hosts (traceroute from load_balancer to a host completes).\n- FRR OSPF appears operational: distribution/server-access routers have OSPF-learned routes for the 10.x.0.0/24 service subnets (examples below).\n\nAnomalous behavior observed\n- Hosts attempting to ping a backend address (20.200.0.2) got this behavior:\n  - From a host (host_1_1_1_1) pinging backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) returned:\n    - “Destination Net Unreachable” returned from the host’s first-hop gateway (10.1.1.1). Traceroute from host1 showed the first hop returning !N.\n    - Example ping/traceroute evidence:\n      - ping host_1_1_1_1 → backend_web_0: 100% failure with “Destination Net Unreachable”.\n      - traceroute from host_1_1_1_1 to 20.200.0.2: 1st hop = 10.1.1.1 with !N.\n- Backend host cannot ping hosts (attempt from backend timed out), indicating asymmetric/unadvertised routing for 20.200.0.0/24 across the routing fabric.\n\nLocalization — where the issue is\n- Server-side segment:\n  - backend_web_0 interface and configuration:\n    - backend_web_0 ip: 20.200.0.2/24, default via 20.200.0.1 (the load_balancer).\n    - backend_web_0 can reach/load balancer (local link).\n  - load_balancer:\n    - has eth1 in 20.200.0.0/24 (20.200.0.1) and eth0 in 10.200.0.0/24 (10.200.0.7).\n    - load_balancer can ping backend addresses successfully and traceroute from load_balancer to hosts reaches the core routers and host.\n- Core/distribution side:\n  - server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected (the server farm) and OSPF routes for customer subnets, but it does NOT show 20.200.0.0/24 in its routing table.\n  - router_dist_1_1 (and by inference other distribution/core routers) does not list 20.200.0.0/24 in its routes — it has 10.200.0.0/24 but no 20.200.0.0/24 entry.\n\nRelevant command evidence (selected)\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\n  - ip route: default via 10.1.1.1\n  - traceroute -> 20.200.0.2: first hop 10.1.1.1 responds with !N (Destination Net Unreachable).\n  - ping to dns_server (10.200.0.2) and web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) succeed.\n- From load_balancer:\n  - ip route shows 10.200.0.0/24 and 20.200.0.0/24 present on appropriate interfaces and default via 10.200.0.1.\n  - traceroute to host shows path through 10.200.0.1 and OSPF-interconnected hops to the host.\n  - ping load_balancer -> backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) succeeds.\n- backend_web_0 net config:\n  - eth0: 20.200.0.2/24, default via 20.200.0.1.\n- FRR routing:\n  - router_dist_1_1 shows OSPF routes for many 10.x and 172.16.x links and 10.200.0.0/24, but no route for 20.200.0.0/24.\n  - server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected and many OSPF routes to 10.x subnets, but no 20.200.0.0/24 advertised.\n\nRoot cause analysis (concise)\n- The 20.200.0.0/24 backend network is not present in the routing fabric used by the hosts (not advertised via OSPF or otherwise injected into the core/distribution routing tables). Hence:\n  - Host packets destined for 20.200.0.0/24 are rejected at their first-hop gateway (the router has no route for that network).\n  - Replies from the backend (even if they leave via the load balancer) will not be accepted/forwarded by the core routers because the core lacks a routing entry for 20.200.0.0/24, causing asymmetry/unreachability.\n- This absence of a route to 20.200.0.0/24 is consistent with the stated design constraint: “by design the backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts.” Therefore, the observed lack of reachability to 20.200.0.0/24 is consistent with either (a) intentional isolation, or (b) a missing advertisement/route if direct routing was expected.\n\nImpact\n- End users/hosts can access published services (DNS, the web servers published in 10.200.0.0/24, and load-balanced service via the load balancer).\n- Back-end servers (20.200.0.0/24) are not reachable directly from host subnets; they remain reachable from the server/load-balancer side only. If direct host → backend reachability were required, the lack of route effectively prevents that traffic (100% packet loss / unreachable).\n- No general OSPF instability or broad connectivity outage was observed; OSPF routes for the rest of the network are present and traffic for the intended service addresses is flowing.\n\nConclusions\n- Network functionality for typical host-to-service flows (using the published service addresses in 10.200.0.0/24 and via the load balancer) is healthy.\n- The only abnormal/unreachable prefix from the host perspective is 20.200.0.0/24. This is due to that subnet not being present in the core/distribution routing tables (not being advertised into OSPF).\n- If the isolation of 20.200.0.0/24 is intentional, the behavior is expected and the network is operating correctly. If it is not intentional, the root cause is missing route advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24 (no OSPF advertisement / missing static route on server_access_router or the load_balancer), and that should be addressed.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- (only on your request) gather FRR configuration showing what networks are advertised (frr_show_running_config / frr_get_ospf_conf) and check whether 20.200.0.0/24 is configured for advertisement, or\n- (only on your request) run further traceroutes/pings from the core routers to 20.200.0.0/24 to pinpoint exactly which router drops/omits the route.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 37138, "output_tokens": 3651, "total_tokens": 40789, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 36480}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1792}}}
